.TH PRINTF 3 "28 Novembre 2024" "1.0" "printf man page"
.SH NAME
.PP
.BI _printf

.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B #include <stdio.h>
.B #include <stdarg.h>
.B int printf(char *format, ...)

.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
.PP
Print output according to format.

Printf is a function that writes output to the stdout, which is the standard output stream.

Also, the function writes the output according to the format string. This format string specifies how the following arguments are converted for output.

.B Return value

The function returns the number of characters printed for success. Note: It excludes the null byte used to end output to strings.

The function returns a negative value if an output error occurs.

.B The conversion specifier

A conversion specifier is a character that specifies the type of conversion to be used. It is used during input and output. It tells the compiler what type of data is in the varaible when printing using printf. 

.B The following conversion specifiers are supported:

.TP 
.B %c 
	Print a single character. 
.TP 
.B %s 
	Print a string of characters. 
.TP 
.B %% 
	Print a percent sign. 
.TP 
.B %d 
	Print a decimal (base 10) number. .
.TP 
.B %i 
	Print an integer in base 10.

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
The following example demonstrates how to use  \fB_printf()\fP:

.nf
.B #include <stdio.h> 

int main(void) 
{
        char name[] = "Brian";
        int age = 25; 

        _printf("Bonjour, je m'appelle %s et j'ai %d ans.\n", name, age);

        return 0; 
}

.B This will Output:
.PP
.nf
Bonjour, je m'appelle Brian et j'ai 25 ans.

.SH NOTES
.PP
This \fB_printf()\fP function is a simplified version of the standard C library printf() function. It lacks some error handling and does not support all the formatting capabilities of the standard printf() function, but it covers the basic usage for the mentioned specifiers.
.PP
Make sure to include the required header files \fI<stdio.h>\fP and \fI<stdarg.h>\fP when using \fB_printf()\fP.

